<!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07 · Recent Commercial Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown · Korean BBQ Restaurant · True T-49</div>
        <h3>"Reach-in stopped cooling overnight, found it warm at morning prep"</h3>
        <p>Condenser fan motor failure on a True T-49 two-door reach-in. The condenser was clean but the fan motor had seized, without airflow over the condenser, the compressor overheated and tripped on its thermal overload. The unit sat warm for approximately 6 hours. Temperature inside was 48°F when we arrived.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced condenser fan motor with OEM True part (carried on van for this exact reason, True is common in LA restaurants). Verified refrigerant charge was within spec. Unit pulled down to 38°F within 90 minutes. Operator was able to assess inventory with confirmed temperature log, most protein product was borderline; we helped document the temperature recovery for their records.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">DTLA Ghost Kitchen · Shared Commercial Kitchen</div>
        <h3>"Ice machine hasn't made ice in two days, three brands sharing it"</h3>
        <p>Commercial Manitowoc ice machine in a shared ghost kitchen facility, the water inlet valve had failed and scale buildup had blocked the water distribution tubes. The machine hadn't been descaled in the 18 months since installation. In LA's hard water environment, Manitowoc recommends descaling every 6 months on shared commercial units.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced water inlet valve, performed full descaling of evaporator and water distribution system. Replaced water filter. Verified ice production within normal range per cycle count. Set a maintenance reminder with the facility manager for 6-month descaling going forward. Downtime was approximately 48 hours, preventable with a scheduled maintenance program.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Hollywood · Cafe · Turbo Air M3R24-2</div>
        <h3>"Under-counter cooler not holding temp, beer and dairy at risk"</h3>
        <p>Failed evaporator fan motor on a Turbo Air under-counter cooler. The compressor was running but without fan circulation, cold air wasn't reaching the front of the unit. The back stayed cold; the front was at 50°F. The cafe had been running this way for several days without realizing the graduated temperature, the owner noticed when beer was warm on the front shelf.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced evaporator fan motor with Turbo Air replacement part. Tested temperature gradient across the full unit before leaving, even 38°F front to back confirmed. Cleaned condenser coils while there (significant dust accumulation in a high-traffic kitchen environment). Advised on monthly coil cleaning as part of regular kitchen cleaning rotation.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena · Laundromat · Speed Queen Commercial</div>
        <h3>"Two washers down on a Saturday, customers turning away"</h3>
        <p>Two Speed Queen front-load commercial washers with different failures, one had a failed door latch that locked mid-cycle and wouldn't release (holding a load of wet laundry hostage), the other had a failed drain pump. Both failures on the same Saturday morning, peak laundromat traffic. Operator called us at 9am.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Arrived at 11:30am. Replaced door latch assembly on unit 1, released the locked load and restored operation. Replaced drain pump on unit 2. Both units tested through full wash cycles before we left. Operator back to full capacity by early afternoon. We now do quarterly preventive maintenance visits for this location, both failures were showing early signs that would have been caught on a maintenance call.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

